<br>
This is the most ignorant steaming pile of bullshit that relegates this entire conflict to a tank model and winter?<br>
<br>
First of all, practically the entire tank park of the Soviet army (~20,000 tanks) had been destroyed in the opening months of the war. which allowed for moderately easy progress during the summber of 41.  The t-34 didnt make a significant difference until the battle of moscow when the siberian divisions were brought up as last ditch reserves from the Far East front and the greater impact was made after Stalingrad since during late 1942-early 1943 is when the USSR rebuilt majority of its tank park.  The t-34 was not even produced in significant numbers to make an impact until 43 and at that time the original cannons had to be reworked from the 75 mm cannon installed on the original model that became obsolete by early 1943 and had to be up graded 2 ways, once to a 76.2 mm cannon and then again to an 85 mm cannon with reinforced chassis.  <br>
<br>
Basically, the T-34 was not produced in significant numbers to make an impact until the USSR turned the tide of war already.  And the problem was not of germans &quot;running out of ammunition to kill a solid chunk of pig iron&quot;  That is the dumbest statement I have ever heard regarding war on the Eastern Front.  USSR was using sloped armor on the front panells of the T-34 chassis.  Its not that the armor was so thick that it was impossible to penetrate, it was because it was so cleverly designed.  And finally.  The Kirov Works mode l 1 tank (KV-1) had better armor and armament up until the 1943 models of the T-34.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;The ONLY thing that allowed what had become a static front to move west AT ALL was the fact that forces had to be taken from the East to once again fight in the West. Before the invasion, the fight in the west was absolutely fucking over. They didn't have to put shit for resources there since they had most of the govenments under their thumbs anyway to 'govern themselves'. &quot; --Maxx<br>
<br>
Lets review some basic facts.  June 22, 1941 germany invades USSR and proceeds in the span of 6 months to demolish and encircle a good portion of their armed forces and make it to miles within Moscow by December.  Zhukov launches a counterattack with the FAr East front divisions that were brought up for Siberia and germans pull back.<br>
Then basically Soviets and germans sit with their thumbs up their asses for 2-3 months until germans launch their spring/summer offensive to get to the oil fields at Caucasus.  Army GroupSotuh demolishes the russian forces making incredible gains until it reaches the Volga.  At this point Army group South splits into Army Group A(AGA) and Army Group B (AGB).  AGA proceeds to the Caucasus mountains to take the oil fields while AGB is ordered to take Stalingrad and then wheel north along the Volga behind Russian lines.<br>
<br>
By August of 1942, AGB aka the 6th army invades Stalingrad.  After a 4 month struggle in the city, Soviets finally launch a counterattack on Nov. 23, 1942 along the north flank and south flank of the 6th army effectively encircling it in 4 days.  The russian winter freezes the germans to death as paulus refuses to break out of the cauldron and Manstein/Hoth are unsuccessful in penetrating the ring at Southwestern point, yada yada yada.  ~ 90,000 german prisoners is whats left alive of the 6th army, a major military and political victory for the allies as Hitler is denied the capture of Stalin's city and his best army is annihillated.  Now that AGB has been destroyed, this leaves AGA in a very bad situation.  The encirclement of the AGB leaves them cut off from the main front line while the russians try to wittle down the encircled 6th army.  By February of 43, 6th army surrenders, so the germans and soviets engage in a bunch of minor front skirmishes up until the summer of 1943 when hitler decided to gamble on kursk salient.  Kursk is directly related to Stalingrad.  At stalingrad, germany is delivered a major political defeat(albeit their military losses were fairly high) but at Kursk, the entire backbone of the Wehrmacht would be borken.  In summer of 1943, ensues the largest tank battle in history of warfare totalling about ~3,000 tanks engaged for both sides.  Germany is delivered a smashing defeat.  Now, After the summer of 43 (Battle of Kursk) the German Army would NEVER mount a major offensive operation in the east ever again.  At which point to take advantage of wehrmacht's vulnerable position, the USSR begins rapidly proceeding forward.  Roughly by the same time as US invaded normandy, USSR had captured parts of finland and karelian peninsula and had entered Poland.  Germans were basically pushed out of USSR by the time of D-Day invasion.  There was NO static front.<br>
<br>
If you have any more questions, please consult me or your local library.  Furthermore, it is this kind of arrogance, righteousness and total lack of actual information that makes people doubt American schools.  <br>
<br>
Merton <br>
