Ok, here is how Finland tied in to the Eastern Front.  First of all, After the Molotov/Ribbentrop Pact USSR felt emboldened and invaded Finalnd in 1940, one year before Germany invaded USSR.  USSR suffered very heavy losses due to very stiff Finnish opposition and the excelent tactical skill of the Finns.  This would play a role later when Germans would siege Leningrad for 900 days and would bombard the civilian population from the northern direction (Finnish territory).  Finns also provided some assistance to the Germans in small skirmishes around Leningrad and were eventually invaded again in 1944 as USSR was reclaiming its territory.  That is how Finland ties in with Eastern Front.<br>
<br>
Now, to the question of static/mobile front.  This is a huge subject which is very difficult to cover in one post, but basically in my previous post i explained major military operations and battles and indicated when there were lulls in fighting as both sides massed forces for ofeensives/defensives and used time to regroup.<br>
<br>
Here's a brief outline and recap just for you.  I can't spell this out anymore easier for you: <br>
<br>
Majority of military action in the East Front happened on Southern and Center fronts of the Eastern Front.  The front did remain moderately static on the Northern portion of East Front around Leningrad/Latvia/Estonia etc. from Winter of 41-42 up until 1944. <br>
<br>
Summer of 41 --- Winter of 41-42   Germans advance from USSR/Poland border to Moscow, sieging Leningrad(sieging it until 1943), capturing Kiev, capturing Minsk, sieging and capturing Odessa.  By the end of 1941, Germany has captured the 3 Baltic states (Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia).  Captured majority of Ukraine, captured practically the entire Belorussia and captured Moldova. <br>
<br>
Winter of 1941-1942   Soviets counterattack at Moscow effectively pushing the Germans away from the capital.  Majority of the front remains static as both sides are focusing their struggle on Moscow.<br>
<br>
Spring of 42  Small skirmish actions in center and southern front portions of East fron resulting in loss/gain of 20-40 miles as Germany masses for a major thrust to the Caucasus.<br>
<br>
Summer of 42  ---  Fall of 42  Germans unleash their spring offensive in Southern Russia which takes them from Kiev and Odessa to Stalingrad.  Roughly a 900 mile advance in 3 months.<br>
<br>
Fall of 42 --- March of 43  Germans are defeated at Stalingrad, Russians counterattack and push them back to the lines at which the Germans began their offensive 9 months ago.  <br>
<br>
April 43 --- July 43.    A lull falls over the Eastern Front as both sides have battled to exhaustion and began to pull together their forces and reinforce positions.<br>
<br>
July 43    Germans strike out at Kursk Salient and engage in the largest tank battle in history that breaks the strength of the Wehrmacht for good.  Very little advance in terms of miles.   The front lines remain fairly unchanged since before Battle of Kursk began.<br>
<br>
July 43 --- November 43   Massive Russian offensive that begins right after the germans start retreating from Kursk.  Germans get pushed to the Dnieper river and Kiev is liberated.  The Front moves westward couple hundred miles along the entire East Front frontline.<br>
<br>
December 43- Summer 44   Russian offensive peters out although advance continues although not on a scale as huge as the offensive second half of 1943.<br>
<br>
&quot;I guess your definition of a mobile front is one that moves 5-10 miles in time periods of months except for isolated areas. Guess what? Thats a static front. For you to say there was no static eastern front is a gross fucking conceptual error of the worst kind. &quot;  -Maxx<br>
<br>
Your statement is very misleading, if you are referring to the Southern front as a &quot;few isolated areas&quot;, you have no concept of the amount of space that was being fought over from spring of 42 to summer of 43.  If you are referring to Northern portion of the front, I might agree.  Northern front remained mostly static until the major Russian offensive in 43 since both sides focused their major efforts on Southern front, and in 1943 at center front (Kursk). I would say that in the offensives that took place every year with Germans typically starting summer offensives and Soviets retaliating with winter offensives, that each offensive would reclaim hundreds of miles of land.  Static front as a whole?  You couldn't be farther from the truth.   Those are just the major points I outlined, not mentioning quick reversals which are too numerous to mention such as the Soviet recapture of Kharkov in March of 43 and the German counter attack that pushed them back 70 miles. Those types of &quot;local&quot; operations are myriad and I dont have the desire to go through them individually.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;The T-34's 10&quot; thick armor wasn't what made it resistant to penetration, it was it's &quot;clever design&quot;? Of course this is a stupid statement to you since you choose to deflect the statement rather than reply to it. You can quote all the bullshit you want from your book but if you actually read it and think about that all that ass you spew but dont understand means, the facts remain that a) There was no 'clever' design of the T-34 that hadn't been done by the germans previously. The armor was sloped where it may encounter high energy shots and it was thick as hell where it counted and very thin where it didn't to save weight. They barely had enough Bessemer furnaces to remove defects before casting when they first started production, it was not high quality metal. Pig iron is exactly what it was and they knew it. This is EXACTLY why the T-34 was good, because basically it was the first thing the Germans encountered that was as diffucult to take out as their own, and they fell into the exact same problem we did with theirs years before.&quot;  -Maxx<br>
<br>
&quot;The T-34 had a major effect on the Russian ability to deal with Panzers and Tigers&quot;  --Maxx<br>
<br>
<br>
According to this   <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.skalman.nu/soviet/ww2-equipment-tank-t34.htm">www.skalman.nu/soviet/ww2...nk-t34.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END-->      and Jane's guide on armored vehicles which is widely considered to be the best civilian resource for military information and statistics, the thickest armor range on even the latest and upgraded T-34 model which was the T-34/85 (85 stands for the upgraded 85 mm cannon which replaced the 76.2 mm cannon) the thickest armor range was 20-90 mm.  Which would equate to 9 cm at highest end.  Which would place the armor thickness at roughly 3.6 - 3.7 inches in the thickest spot.  A very far cry from the 10 inches of thickness that you claim.  Please stop quoting made up facts and statistics that you know absolutely nothing about.<br>
<br>
You claim that my statement of the T-34 having a clever design is stupid?   You might want to consult these websites.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/row/t-34.htm">www.fas.org/man/dod-101/s...w/t-34.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;The T-34 was a technologically innovative design which addressed the short-comings of the earlier BT series of wheel/track tank. &quot;  --Website mentioned above.<br>
<br>
&quot;The design overcame the technological superiority of German forces during the Great Patriotic War.&quot;  --Website mentioned above<br>
<br>
&quot;The T-34 had a more powerful cannon than German tanks, a higher top speed (32 MPH versus 25 MPH), and superior sloped armor and superior welded construction&quot; (Note the mention of superior sloped armor)  --Website mentioned above<br>
<br>
&quot;The T-34/85 was a modification of the T-34 equipped with a more powerful armor and cannon. T-34/85 had a flatter turret which gave this already inovative tank design the look that all tanks adopted after the wars end. Although not equal to the German Panther and Tiger tanks, the huge numbers of T-34s more than compensated for their technological shortcomings&quot;  (Note where it says that the Russian T-34 was not equal to Tigers and Panthers thus debunking this statement:  &quot;The T-34 had a major effect on the Russian ability to deal with Panzers and Tigers&quot;  --Maxx)  --Website Mentioned above<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.soviet-empire.com/arsenal/army/tanks/t34.php">www.soviet-empire.com/ars...ks/t34.php</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;It featured a high velocity gun placing more emphasis on tank killing ability and its armour was very well sloped making it difficult to knock out&quot;  --Website mentioned above   (note the mention of the sloped armour which was the clever design I was referring to)<br>
<br>
Obviously you dont even have a clue about these tanks.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
And finally...<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;Your whole point that the western allies had little to do with victory in WWII shoots holes in your credibility before you even open your mouth to say more. Unload all the crap you want about this unit here and that one there but guess what? It doesn't change the fact that the whole basis of your argument is dick, and anyone who doesn't have a 'dumb American' agenda will agree.&quot;  --Maxx<br>
<br>
Here's something to think about.  90% of German casualties in the entire Second World War were on Eastern Front.<br>
<br>
<br>
Anyways, speaking of holes in arguments, I think I exposed enough of them in yours.  Please, next time you try to speak include some actual data to back up your statements and try not to get emotional.  Its not your fault that everyone talks about how wonderfully impressive D-Day was but no one even remebers places like Stalingrad, Kursk, Leningrad, Minsk.  Places which had as many people die every day for months as the first day of D-Day.  The key thing to remember is that by 1944 when D-Day was landed, Russia effectively and single-handedly broke the back of the German army and whatever was left of the Wehrmacht, was just a demoralized, ill-supplied mass of survivors of previous battles and green recruits for the most part.<br>
<br>
Like I said, please consult your local library, I'm tired of going through this every time some idiot opens their mouth and yaps something they know absolutely jack about.  <br>
